Abstract = {{Patent systems have been established as an incentive for innovation in
   most countries of the world. However, small and medium enterprises
   (SMEs) typically have little experience and expertise in using such
   systems. This paper examines the impact of Japanese patent infringement
   litigation on the subsequent patenting behavior of plaintiff SMEs. Our
   results show that SMEs tend to file lower numbers of patent applications
   but gain stronger patent rights after experiencing patent infringement
   litigation as plaintiffs. This suggests that SMEs learn to manage their
   patent applications after experiencing patent litigation as plaintiffs.
   Furthermore, we also find that the high costs to of patent litigation
   lead to a subsequent decrease in both patent application counts and the
   maximum number of forward citations of granted patents after litigation.
